text: Ten days left to vote!! UScellular’s third annual Black History Month Art Contest with the Boys & Girls Clubs of the Mississippi Valley. Voting is available online. This year, UScellular introduced an exciting new element to the contest. For the first time, Boys & Girls Clubs of the Mississippi Valley members were encouraged to create their original pieces of artwork in recognition of influential Black STEM icons that include historical figures, world leaders, scientists and educators. Boys & Girls Clubs of the Mississippi Valley representatives selected the 10 finalists based on creativity, quality, interpretation, clarity of theme and overall impression. The artists range in age from 6 to 12 years old. They are from Davenport and Moline. Voting is open until Feb. 28 at https://uscellular.sjc1.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_73bD2JvHQzNURMO. Anyone 18 years or older can vote for their favorite piece of art. Individuals also can view a digital artwork display that features the 10 finalists at UScellular’s Kimberly retail store, 351 W. Kimberly Road in Davenport. The top three vote-getters will be announced in March. Prizes include gift cards in the following amounts: • $250 for first place • $150 for second place • $100 for third place

AISHA ‘PINKY’ COLE (SLUTTY VEGAN) | JAMAICAN | @pinky907 | Cole was born and raised in Baltimore. Her parents are Jamaican immigrants and Rastafarians. Cole is the founder of Slutty Vegan, a plant based burger spot in Atlanta and she is also a philanthropist; in 2020, she partnered with Clark Atlanta University to provide the children of police brutality victim Rayshard Brooks $600,000 in scholarships to the historically black university. #CaribbeanAmericanHeritageMonth
We want to continue to introduce our board members and thank them for all that they do to help our alumni stay connected and engaged with Lee Unviersity.

KALILAH WRIGHT (MESS IN A BOTTLE) | JAMAICAN | @ownerofmess | Kalilah Wright, born in Jamaica W.I., migrated to the United States at the tender age of 4 and was raised in Brooklyn, NY. She is the Founder and CEO of expressive brand Mess in a Bottle. Wright said being a Black woman and an immigrant Black woman is what motivates her drive and purpose in her businesses. Wright also wanted to use her platform to elevate other Black women to achieve their dreams. #CaribbeanAmericanHeritageMonth

May is Asian/Pacific American Heritage Month – a celebration of Asians, Native Hawaiians and Pacific Islanders in the United States. A rather broad term, Asian/Pacific encompasses all of the Asian continent and the Pacific islands of Melanesia (New Guinea, New Caledonia, Vanuatu, Fiji and the Solomon Islands), Micronesia (Marianas, Guam, Wake Island, Palau, Marshall Islands, Kiribati, Nauru and the Federated States of Micronesia) and Polynesia (New Zealand, Hawaiian Islands, Rotuma, Midway Islands, Samoa, American Samoa, Tonga, Tuvalu, Cook Islands, French Polynesia and Easter Island). The month of May was chosen to commemorate the immigration of the first Japanese to the United States on May 7, 1843, and to mark the anniversary of the completion of the transcontinental railroad on May 10, 1869. The majority of the workers who laid the tracks were Chinese immigrants. Looking for ways to celebrate Asian / Pacific American Heritage month? Check out San Francisco's Asian Art Museum calendar of events to get involved in the celebration! The Asian Art Museum is offering many online discussions and events so even if you aren't in the city by the bay, you can join in and learn more about the richness and diversity of Asian Americans, Hawaiians and Pacific Islander Americans. #asianamerican #pacificislanderamerican #pacificislanderheritage #asianheritage #asianheritagemonth2022 #diversity #celebration #india #ayurveda #culture #culturaldiversity

Tsai Ing-wen is the first female President of the Republic of China (Taiwan) and a member of the Taiwanese Democratic Progressive Party. She supports disadvantaged groups, favors LGBTQ+ rights, and champions bipartisanship, labor reform, and green energy. What can’t she do? Not only are the people of Taiwan #BetterBecauseOfHer — we all are. #WHM2022 #EmpowerWomen

Not just anyone can be the youngest person ever awarded the Nobel Peace Prize! Malala Yousafzai is a human rights activist and a UN Messenger of Peace — but these titles don’t do justice to the incredible work that Malala has done in her short life. Malala’s name is synonymous with inspiration — her advocacy has evolved into an unstoppable international movement. “I tell my story not because it is unique,” says Malala, “but because it is the story of so many girls.” We are #BetterBecauseOfHer #WHM2022 #EmpowerWomen

The leader of @MacquarieGroup, a global financial services firm, Shemara Wikramanayake is intent on using private capital for solutions to our existential climate issues. Not only has Shemara led her company to record profits since she began her tenure, she has also thrown herself headfirst into the weeds of creating a new low-carbon normal. Her aim is simple and elegant: to invest in the climate — and to inspire others to do so, too. We are #BetterBecauseOfHer. #WHM2022

Celebrating Black History, Black People.       This year’s theme for #BlackHistoryMonth focuses on the importance of Black Health and Wellness, acknowledging the legacy of activities, rituals and initiatives that Black communities have done to be well. We are celebrating and sharing wisdom from some of our Black, MNDFL Certified Instructors who are being well through mindfulness.      Meet Kathleen Dameron     “Une noire. In French my blackness and my femaleness live in one word. As do I.   I notice a world around me constantly measuring my existence: ‘too Black’, ‘not Black enough’, ‘we don’t even see you are Black’, ‘You’ve got real balls’.   I give notice: Je suis noire. Your measuring is NOT my story. NOT a game I play.   MY blackness is in my vibration, my walk, my connection to lifeforce that finds joy for no reason. I just am……. constantly, immeasurably, bodaciously NOIRE.”     - Kathleen Dameron (she/her), MNDFL Certified, MNDFL Facilitator   kathleendameron.com        Black. MNDFL. Certified.       Mindfulness isn't one size or one voice fits all. When you train with us, you train with people that look like the world does. 🚨There is still time to register for the May Book Club discussion! Book Club will meet on May 12th to discuss Minor Feelings by Cathy Park Hong. Hong dissects her experiences as an Asian American to create an intricate meditation on racial awareness in the U.S. Through a combination of cultural criticism and personal stories, Hong, a poet, lays bare the shame and confusion she felt in her youth as the daughter of Korean immigrants, and the way those feelings morphed as she grew older. From analyzing Richard Pryor’s stand-up to interrogating her relationship with the English language, Hong underscores essential themes of identity and otherness. 👉Books are available for checkout at the Advanced Learning Library. Register for the discussion here: https://wichita.evanced.info/signup/eventdetails?EventId=12526

DANCING IN THE MOSQUE by Homeira Qaderi tells the story of a mother and her struggles through oppression, an abusive Patriarchy, a divorce, and an ultimate sacrifice to leave Afghanistan. Once her son is born her plan to flee the country and study in America is brought to a halt by her husband. In order to free herself as a woman she must leave behind her son. This is Homeria’s letter to her son on why she left while also exploring her journey into living outside of the oppressive laws that ultimately made her leave her son behind. Harper Perennial

#WomensHistoryMonth • Chante’ Adams Chante’ Adams born and raised in Detroit is now a successful actress! But, her favorite childhood memories go back to her time with PAL when she participated in our cheerleading program. Chante loved the adrenaline rush of cheer competitions in a stadium as cheer teams competed and encouraged one another. PAL gave her something healthy and fun to look forward to during summer breaks and was an important part of her life and childhood. Chante’ said, “The PAL organization is vital to the city and the children." Chante’ is known for being in many great films including: A Journal For Jordan, The Photograph, Roxanne Roxanne, Bad Hair, Monsters and Men, and much more! The programs we offer at PAL for Detroit youth are changing lives forever.

African Americans are at increased risk for chronic kidney disease (CKD). About 37 million American adults have CKD and most don’t even know it. Early detection and treatment can prevent complications from kidney disease. Black K.A.R.E. — which stands for “Kidney Awareness, Resources, and Education” — has launched an online toolkit to provide resources, information, and more about Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD), self-care for kidney health, diagnosis and treatment, and much more. https://healthcoreclinic.org/2022/05/02/blackkare-kidney-awareness-resources-and-education

As part of our larger network, HCA Healthcare, we are committed to reducing health disparities and advancing health equity. The negative impacts of the pandemic have affected these women at a higher rate than male owned and non-minority counterparts. This is based on the concentration of Asian-owned businesses in essential industries such as hospitality, retail, and education services. Additionally, they've faced an increase in racism and xenophobia which has resulted in attacks on businesses and individuals. At WISE Women's Business Center, we work to empower and enable economically and socially disadvantaged women through action. Check out our website today to explore our resources and programs. (These statistics and information were provided by the National Association of Women Business Owners (NAWBO))

Did you know that May is Asian American and Pacific Islander Heritage Month? May was chosen because of two key dates, May 7th and May 10th. May 7th, 1843, marks the arrival of the first Japanese immigrants to the United States. As for May 10th, or Golden Spike Day, in 1869, recognizes the completion of the first transcontinental railroad in the US. This railroad had significant contributions from Chinese immigrant workers, and was a key component in the industrialization of the US, changing the business and economic landscape forever. Join WISE in celebrating AAPI contributions this May by recognizing AAPI contributions and statistics.

📣We call on the Biden Administration to end all Title 42 expulsions immediately. 🔴Update on Title 42 - What do the recent court rulings mean for families seeking asylum? Title 42 allows the U.S. to rapidly expel migrants coming into the country, without reviewing asylum needs or following mandated deportation procedures (which can often take months to go into effect). This is all done under the guise of “public health safety” at the same time that the U.S. is rolling back on other very important safety practices. Yet, Title 42 had no effect on the many white Ukrainian refugees that sought asylum during COVID - this is because this policy has nothing to do with public health, it is an excuse to target brown immigrants specifically at the Mexican border. 2 court rulings were revealed March 4th 2022, both taking place on the same day and directly opposing each other. While the D.C. court of appeals ruled to block the government from sending families to places where they could face persecution or danger. However, the court reminded silent regarding the broad boundaries of this ruling which leaves a scary amount of leeway for the U.S. government to continue to expel migrants seeking refuge. Furthermore, this decision will only apply to families traveling with minor children, therefore, all other asylum-seekers could still be expelled under Title 42 in the same way as before—even if they showed that they faced likely persecution. Meanwhile, the Texas court ruling which took place only a few hours after D.C. had the opposite conclusion. Judge Mark Pittman argued that the Biden administration had no right to exempt unaccompanied minors from expulsion under Title 42 because such an exemption was “arbitrary and capricious.” Biden has the choice to continue rapidly deporting immigrants, now including the minors in government custody, back into deadly situations of persecution - or - he can end it all by repealing Title 42.

Today, we’re celebrating #BlackHerstoryMonth by celebrating the life and legacy of our very own Dr. Dorothy Height. Known as the “godmother of the civil rights movement,” she dedicated her life to the intersectional mission of racial and gender equality and inspired other well-known civil rights leaders, including Martin Luther King. #bhm2022 Dorothy was one of the nation’s most steadfast civil rights activists, whose intersectional activism as our first Director of Racial Justice led to YWCA’s One Imperative to #EliminateRacism, wherever it exists, by any means necessary. #EliminateRacism #EmpowerWomen #Blackhistory365 #BlackFeminists #BlackHistoryMonth #BHM2022

Angela Davis, a key figure in the U.S. civil rights movement, made significant contributions and influence in the fight for #racialjustice, women's rights, and criminal justice reform. Through her activism and scholarship over the last decades, her work as an educator – both at the university level and in the larger public sphere – has always emphasized the importance of building communities of struggle for economic, racial, and gender justice. In recent years, her work has been the range of social problems associated with incarceration and the generalized criminalization of those communities that are most affected by poverty and racial discrimination, drawing on her own experiences in the early seventies as a person who spent eighteen months in jail and on trial, after being placed on the FBI’s “Ten Most Wanted List.” Today, she continues to be an activist and lecturer as Professor Emeritus of History of Consciousness and Feminist Studies at the University of California at Santa Cruz. She is also a Distinguished Visiting Professor in the Women's and Gender Studies Department at Syracuse University. #BlackHerstoryMonth

We're continuing our discussion of Alice Walker today by discussing her legacy of social activism in her family. In 1967, Alice Walker and her then-husband became the first legally married interracial couple in Mississippi, and in 1969, they had their daughter Rebecca, a social activist in her own right. Continuing her mom’s critical work at the intersection of racial and gender equality, Rebecca coined the term Third Wave Feminism, an intersectional movement of which she is a prominent voice. Read Rebecca's 1992 article on feminism "Becoming the Third Wave" 👉 bit.ly/35sxH8K:=:https://teachrock.org/wp-content/uploads/Handout-1-Rebecca-Walker-%E2%80%9CI-Am-the-Third-Wave%E2%80%9D.pdf?x96081 #BlackHerstoryMonth2022

Meet Kimberle Crenshaw, a pioneering civil rights advocate, professor, and leading critical race theory scholar known for not only working at the intersection of race and gender, but for coining the term #intersectionality to call attention to how systems of oppression overlap to create distinct experiences for those with multiple identity categories. Among her many contributions is co-founding and founding and leading African American Policy Forum, an intersectional think tank behind campaigns such as #SayHerName, which calls attention to police violence against Black women and girls. #BlackHerstoryMonth

During #BlackHerstoryMonth, we can’t talk about #BlackFeminists without uplifting the life and works of Audre Lorde. As a self-described “Black, lesbian, mother, warrior, poet,” Lorde dedicated her life to grappling with the critical and often intersecting injustices of racism, classism, sexism, and homophobia. She was a vigilant champion for Black queer women whose critiques of the racism within feminist movements offered a voice to Black women who often felt unseen and left behind. Her radical perspectives helped forge the way for the contemporary radical Black feminists of today and created pathways for unity across the social divides she navigated in her own life.

As the only woman in her law school class, it was at Howard University where #PauliMurray developed one of her most influential and prescient theories #JaneCrow. As she became increasingly aware of the conjunction of racism and sexism in her own life, and in the lives of other Black women, Murray used the expression #JaneCrow — alluding to “Jim Crow,” the discriminatory system of state and local laws that enforced racial segregation in the southern United States — to articulate how racial and gender-based oppressions combined to circumscribe Black women’s freedom, a theory that would later become known as #intersectionality. It is at the intersection of race and gender where YWCAs across the country meet to do the work to #eliminateracism, #empowerwomen, and create a world of peace, justice, freedom, and dignity for all. #BlackHerstoryMonth

🎉 #BlackHerstoryMonth starts TODAY! 🎉 The perspectives of #BlackFeminists have consistently transformed the fights for gender equity and racial justice to ensure we can continue to build a world of equity, justice, and freedom for all. That’s why, all this month, we’re celebrating Black feminism and centering the work of powerful Black SHEroes past and present doing the critical intersectional work to #EliminateRacism and #EmpowerWomen. Follow along all month long as we center the unsung legacy of Black feminism: from Jane Crow to Intersectionality.

Mari Copeny (AKA Little Miss Flint) is a 14-year-old activist shining a spotlight on environmental racism, particularly in her hometown of Flint, MI. Her activism around this issue helped bring national attention to the Flint Water Crisis and prompted then-President Obama to approve $100 million in relief money to address the issue. Since then, she has continued her activism in Flint as well as in the area of environmental racism globally. Flint, MI is #BetterBecauseOfHer. #BetterBecauseOfHer #WomensHistoryMonth #WHM2022 #EmpoweredWomen

Join us for an evening with New York Times bestselling authors Erik Larson and Abbott Kahler, aka Karen Abbott! Enjoy a live conversation discussing #1 bestseller The Splendid and The Vile from the comfort of your living room on Wednesday, March 9th from 7 to 8pm. Signed books will be included with ticket purchase. In The Splendid and the Vile, Erik Larson shows, in cinematic detail, how Churchill taught the British people “the art of being fearless.” It is a story of political brinkmanship, but it’s also an intimate domestic drama, set against the backdrop of Churchill’s prime-ministerial country home, Chequers; his wartime retreat, Ditchley, where he and his entourage go when the moon is brightest and the bombing threat is highest; and of course, 10 Downing Street in London. Drawing on diaries, original archival documents, and once-secret intelligence reports—some released only recently—Larson provides a new lens on London’s darkest year through the day-to-day experience of Churchill and his family: his wife, Clementine; their youngest daughter, Mary, who chafes against her parents’ wartime protectiveness; their son, Randolph, and his beautiful, unhappy wife, Pamela; Pamela’s illicit lover, a dashing American emissary; and the advisers in Churchill’s “Secret Circle,” to whom he turns in the hardest moments. Link to purchase tickets: https://bit.ly/LarsonLibrary:=:https://phoenixvillelibrary.salsalabs.org/larson/index.html
